---
import AiPage from '../layouts/AiPage.astro';
---
<AiPage
  title="What are AI evals? How to measure if your AI output is actually good | KB Cafe"
  description="An AI eval is a repeatable test that measures whether a model's output is good enough, the difference between 'it seemed to work' and 'it works 94% of the time on these cases.' The anatomy of an eval, the four ways to score output (exact match, rubric, LLM-as-judge, human), the honest caveats, and a picker that matches a method to your task."
  path="/what-are-ai-evals"
  eyebrow="AI Explained · Practice"
  h1="What are AI evals?"
  tagline="If a prompt change fixes one case and silently breaks three others, how would you know? Evals are how. They turn 'it felt better' into a number you can track, the verify gate from loops, applied at scale."
>
  <h2>The problem evals solve</h2>
  <p>
    LLM output is non-deterministic and easy to fool yourself about. You tweak a prompt, the one example you tried looks
    great, you ship, and three other cases quietly regressed. An <strong>eval</strong> (short for evaluation) is a
    repeatable test that measures output quality across many cases, so &ldquo;it seemed to work&rdquo; becomes &ldquo;it
    passes 47 of 50.&rdquo; It is the same idea as the verify gate in <a href="/what-are-ai-loops">AI loops</a>, scaled
    from one run to a whole test set, and it is how you catch <a href="/what-is-an-ai-hallucination">hallucinations</a>
    before users do.
  </p>

  <h2>The anatomy of an eval</h2>
  <p>
    Every eval has three parts: a <strong>dataset</strong> of inputs (often with an expected output or a rubric), a
    <strong>scorer</strong> that decides pass or fail (or a number) for each, and a <strong>metric</strong> you track over
    time. Run it after every prompt or model change and it becomes regression testing for AI: you see instantly whether a
    change helped overall or just helped the one case you were staring at. A small, carefully chosen set of real cases
    beats a huge sloppy one.
  </p>

  <h2>The four ways to score</h2>
  <p>
    Picking the right scorer is the whole game, and it depends entirely on what &ldquo;good&rdquo; means for your task:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Exact / deterministic</strong>: the output must match a known answer, or pass a test, a regex, or a JSON schema. Cheap, fast, and unambiguous. Best when there is one right answer (extraction, classification, code that must pass tests).</li>
    <li><strong>Rubric scoring</strong>: grade against an explicit checklist (covers the key points, right tone, no banned phrases). Best for open-ended quality where there is no single correct string.</li>
    <li><strong>LLM-as-judge</strong>: a second model scores the output against your criteria. This scales rubric grading to thousands of cases for cents, but the judge is itself a model, it can be biased or gamed, so you validate it against human scores before trusting it.</li>
    <li><strong>Human review</strong>: the gold standard. Slow and expensive, reserved for high-stakes decisions and for calibrating the cheaper methods above.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="ev" id="ev">
    <div class="ev-head">Hands-on: pick the eval method</div>
    <p class="ev-sub">For each task, which scoring method fits best?</p>
    <p class="ev-q" id="ev-q"></p>
    <div class="ev-opts" id="ev-opts"></div>
    <p class="ev-reveal" id="ev-reveal" hidden></p>
    <div class="ev-foot"><span id="ev-prog"></span><button id="ev-next" type="button" hidden>Next &rarr;</button></div>
  </div>

  <h2>The honest caveats</h2>
  <p>
    Evals are powerful and easy to misuse. Three rules keep them honest: <strong>validate your judge</strong>, an
    LLM-as-judge is not ground truth until you have checked its scores against human ones on a sample. <strong>Do not
    optimize to the eval</strong>, if you tune endlessly against the same 50 cases, you start fitting the test instead of
    the task (Goodhart&rsquo;s law). And <strong>keep a holdout</strong>, some cases you do not look at while iterating, so
    your number reflects real performance, not memorized answers. An eval you have quietly gamed is worse than none,
    because it gives false confidence.
  </p>

  <h2>Where to go next</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/what-are-ai-loops">AI loops</a>, where a single eval becomes the gate that decides when to stop.</li>
    <li><a href="/what-is-an-ai-hallucination">Hallucinations</a>, the failure mode evals are built to catch.</li>
    <li><a href="/what-are-structured-outputs">Structured outputs</a>, what makes exact-match scoring possible.</li>
  </ul>
</AiPage>

<style is:global>
  .ev{border:1.5px solid var(--line);border-radius:14px;background:var(--cream);padding:16px 18px;margin:24px 0}
  .ev-head{font-family:var(--font-mono);font-size:11px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--coral)}
  .ev-sub{font-size:14px;color:var(--ink-soft);margin:8px 0 12px}
  .ev-q{font-size:15.5px;font-weight:600;line-height:1.5;color:var(--ink);background:var(--paper-2);border-radius:10px;padding:13px 15px;margin:0 0 12px}
  .ev-opts{display:flex;flex-wrap:wrap;gap:8px}
  .ev-opts button{border:1.5px solid var(--line);background:var(--paper);border-radius:10px;padding:8px 13px;font-family:var(--font-mono);font-size:12.5px;color:var(--ink);cursor:pointer;transition:border-color .12s,background .12s}
  .ev-opts button:hover{border-color:var(--coral)}
  .ev-opts button:disabled{cursor:default}
  .ev-opts button.right{border-color:#0f9f82;background:rgba(15,159,130,.12)}
  .ev-opts button.wrong{border-color:var(--coral);background:rgba(238,75,43,.08)}
  .ev-reveal{margin:12px 0 0;font-size:14px;line-height:1.55;color:var(--ink);background:var(--paper-2);border-radius:10px;padding:11px 13px}
  .ev-foot{display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:space-between;margin-top:12px;min-height:30px}
  .ev-foot span{font-family:var(--font-mono);font-size:12px;color:var(--ink-soft)}
  #ev-next{border:0;background:var(--coral);color:#fff;font-family:var(--font-display);font-weight:700;font-size:13px;padding:7px 15px;border-radius:9px;cursor:pointer}
</style>

<script is:inline>
  (function () {
    var OPTS = ['Exact match', 'Rubric', 'LLM-as-judge', 'Human review'];
    var Q = [
      { task: 'Check that the model pulled the correct invoice total from 500 receipts.', a: 0, why: 'Exact match. There is one right number per receipt, so a deterministic comparison is fast, free, and unambiguous. No judgment needed.' },
      { task: 'Score whether 2,000 support replies are on-brand and genuinely helpful.', a: 2, why: 'LLM-as-judge. The quality is somewhat subjective and the volume is too high for humans, so a model grades against your rubric, after you validate it on a sample.' },
      { task: 'Decide if an AI-written medical summary is safe to send to a patient.', a: 3, why: 'Human review. High stakes and real harm if wrong, so a qualified person signs off. Use the cheaper methods to triage, never to decide alone.' },
      { task: 'Confirm generated code actually works.', a: 0, why: 'Exact / deterministic. Run the test suite: it passes or it fails. Code is the easiest thing to eval because the gate is unambiguous.' },
      { task: 'During early prototyping, rate the helpfulness of 30 draft answers against a checklist.', a: 1, why: 'Rubric. Small set, open-ended quality, and you want to understand the failures. Score by hand against explicit criteria before automating anything.' }
    ];
    var i = 0, answered = false;
    var qEl = document.getElementById('ev-q'), optsEl = document.getElementById('ev-opts'),
        rev = document.getElementById('ev-reveal'), prog = document.getElementById('ev-prog'), next = document.getElementById('ev-next');
    function show() {
      answered = false; qEl.textContent = Q[i].task; optsEl.innerHTML = '';
      OPTS.forEach(function (o, k) { var b = document.createElement('button'); b.type = 'button'; b.textContent = o; b.dataset.k = k; optsEl.appendChild(b); });
      rev.hidden = true; next.hidden = true; prog.textContent = 'Task ' + (i + 1) + ' of ' + Q.length;
    }
    optsEl.addEventListener('click', function (e) {
      var b = e.target.closest('button'); if (!b || answered) return; answered = true;
      var k = +b.dataset.k, ok = k === Q[i].a;
      Array.prototype.forEach.call(optsEl.children, function (c) {
        c.disabled = true;
        if (+c.dataset.k === Q[i].a) c.classList.add('right'); else if (c === b) c.classList.add('wrong');
      });
      rev.innerHTML = (ok ? '<strong>Correct.</strong> ' : '<strong>The better fit is ' + OPTS[Q[i].a] + '.</strong> ') + Q[i].why;
      rev.hidden = false; next.hidden = (i >= Q.length - 1);
      if (i >= Q.length - 1) prog.textContent = 'Done, all ' + Q.length + ' seen.';
    });
    next.addEventListener('click', function () { if (i < Q.length - 1) { i++; show(); } });
    show();
  })();
</script>
